<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br>
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Smith (2017) indicated that&hellip;
	<br>
	Alternatively: A recent study (Smith, 2017) indicated that&hellip;
</blockquote>
<br>
When the author is referred to more than once, in the same paragraph, cite the work the first time 
that it is referred to in your writing. Once the work is cited, it is not necessary to include the 
citation again, as long as it is clear that you are referring to the same work and that it cannot be 
confused with other sources being paraphrased. Repeat the citation again, if the paraphrase continues 
into the next paragraph.  
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	In a recent study, Smith (2017) showed that&hellip; Smith also found that&hellip;
</blockquote>
<br>
If you are using a direct quotation, consisting of fewer than 40 words, enclose the quote using double 
quotation marks and include page numbers.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Smith (2017) observed that &#34;students perform better when rested&#34; (p. 56).
	<br>
	Alternatively: Therefore, &#34;students perform better when rested&#34; (Smith, 2017, p. 56).
</blockquote>
